<SLUG fv=tia-z> BC-VALUJET-NTSB-REPEAT-B </SLUG>
<DATE> 05-21 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0667 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-VALUJET-NTSB-REPEAT-BLOOM
SABRETECH SAYS IT DELIVERED MISLABELED BOX TO VALUJET (REPEAT)
(For use by New York Times News Service clients)
By Jeff Vinson
c.1996 Bloomberg Business News
   (Repeats story that moved late yesterday; adds comments from
Quinn in paragraphs 3-4)
Atlanta, May 20 (Bloomberg) -- SabreTech has opened an ``exhaustive
investigation'' into why its employees delivered to ValuJet Inc. a
box of oxygen generators marked as ``empty,'' said a spokesman for
the Miami aircraft repair facility.
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   ``We acknowledge that SabreTech delivered to ValuJet boxes
containing the canisters with a shipping ticket marked as`empty',''
said Dave Reddick, a spokesman for shipper's parent company.
``We're certainly concerned about this.''
<p>
   Kenneth P. Quinn, a SabreTech spokesman in Miami, said late
yesterday that his company, ``consistent with past practice,''
returned ValuJet materials to the airline for ``appropriate
disposal.''
<p>
   ``ValuJet made an independent decision to ship their company
materials on board an aircraft, and apparently did not ensure that
they were properly labeled, packaged and stored,'' Quinn said.
<p>
   ValuJet officials said the airline wasn't informed that cargo
flight 592 was hazardous.
<p>
   Hazardous materials experts investigating the May 11 crash of
the discount carrier's DC-9 in Florida's Everglades earlier this
month found evidence that exploding oxygen canisters in the cargo
hold may have caused the accident, which killed 110 people.
<p>
   The National Transportation Safety Board reported that divers
found metal fragments from oxygen canisters that apparently
exploded and burned before the plane crashed. Five boxes of oxygen
generators were presented for shipment to Atlanta from Miami by
non-ValuJet employees, and someone filled out the ticket to read:
``5 boxes, oxy canisters empty,'' ValuJet said in a statement. The
shipment was delivered to ValuJet in boxes without the federally
required hazardous material labeling or any other indication of the
hazardous goods within, ValuJet said. SabreTech removed the expired
canisters from three ValuJet MD-80 aircraft, the NTSB said. Two or
three months later, a SabreTech official ordered them returned to
ValuJet. Consistent with ValuJet's statement, NTSB lead
investigator Gregory Feith said the boxes were marked as company
material, the shipping manifest said the canisters were ``empty.''
<p>
   About 119 oxygen canisters were in the cargo hold, more than
double the amount originally thought, Feith said. No plastic safety
caps were used to cover the firing mechanisms on the canisters, he
said. ``We're cooperating fully with the NTSB, the FAA and
Department'' to find out why the box was mislabeled, Reddick said.
<p>
   Sabreliner, a St. Louis-based company that specializes in engine
overhaul and structural modification of government and civilian
aircraft, purchased SabreTech, formerly known as DynAire, last
year, Reddick said. He said this is the first time an incident like
this has happened at SabreTech. ``We are very proud of our very
good safety record, and we're doing everything possible to check to
see that the proper procedures are followed,'' Reddick said. On
Sunday, ValuJet President Lewis Jordan ask Americans to wait for
the results of the federal probe before abandoning the troubled
airline.
<p>
   ``We think it would be a tragedy for the American people who
can't afford high fares to not have ValuJet around,'' Jordan on ABC
TV's ``This Week with David Brinkley.'' ValuJet, based in Atlanta,
cut its number of daily flights in half during a special Federal
Aviation Administration safety inspection of its 51 planes. The FAA
has launched an ``intensive review'' of the airline, which follows
a special 120-day investigation that started last February after a
string of safety-related incidents.
<p>
   In trading today, ValuJet shares closed at 11 1/4, down 1 7/8,
the most active issue. ValuJet shares have fallen more than 27
percent since the crash.
</TEXT>
