<STORYID cat=a pri=r> A9282 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tad-z> BC-WHISTLEBLOWER-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> 06-04 </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0760 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-WHISTLEBLOWER-COX
WHISTLEBLOWER SHIELD: AVIATION WORKERS WANT PROTECTION WHEN THEY
REPORT TROUBLE
By MACON MOREHOUSE
c. 1996 Cox News Service
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   ATLANTA  &MD;  Flight attendant Nancy Chagares says when she heard
that a ValuJet plane, just deemed unairworthy by a pilot, had taken
off with a new crew and passengers, she didn't hesitate to report
it to her supervisors.
<p>
   For her effort, she says, she was forced to resign.
<p>
   ``If you raise questions about anything, by God, they are going
to get rid of you,'' she says.
<p>
   A ValuJet spokesman said the airline investigated Chagares'
claims about the incident last New Year's Eve and did not force her
out of her job.
<p>
   But stories like hers have prompted aviation employees to fight
for the same protection thousands of other workers have: the
freedom to fight back legally if they are punished for blowing the
whistle.
<p>
   A bill pending in Congress would bar airlines and their
contractors from discriminating against an employee who reports
safety problems. Violations could be reported to the U.S.
Department of Labor or, eventually, a federal court.
<p>
   Supporters say they hope last month's fatal crash of ValuJet
Flight 592 helps speed passage of the law. A hearing before a
congressional subcommittee could be held as early as July 10.
<p>
   ``On any airline, if there are problems, it's the people working
on the planes who will see them,'' said Jill Gallagher, spokeswoman
for the Association of Flight Attendants. ``Relying on the workers
would be a good thing.''
<p>
   U.S. Rep. James Clyburn (D-S.C.), who introduced the bill, said
the fatal crash of a USAir flight in Charlotte two years ago
prompted his concern.
<p>
   ``I take at least four flights a week,'' he said. ``For me to
sit there knowing a flight attendant is not on the team making sure
I am safe (because of a fear to report problems) is unbelievable.''
<p>
   ValuJet and Delta, both based in Atlanta, say they do protect
employees who report problems and have telephone lines that
employees can call anonymously. Both say they encourage employees
to talk to their supervisors and do not discipline them for
reporting problems.
<p>
   ``It's an open-door policy,'' said ValuJet spokesman Gregg
Kenyon. They also may report concerns to the Federal Aviation
Administration, but ValuJet prefers that they do not go to the news
media, spokeswoman Marcia Scott said.
<p>
   Valujet flight attendant Anna Wooten said on ABC's ``Nightline''
last month that ``flight attendants are afraid to say anything.''
When the reporter mentioned that she was still working for the
airline, she replied, ``Probably won't be after this interview.''
<p>
   Wooten currently is on maternity leave, Scott said.
<p>
   Chagares, a former Atlantic Southeast Airlines flight attendant,
said her problems began a little more than three weeks after she
started working for ValuJet.
<p>
   She said she was working in the airline's Atlanta operations
center Dec. 31 when a pilot came in and told the operations
supervisor that his plane needed several days worth of maintenance
and he would not fly it.
<p>
   The pilot was assigned to a different plane, she said, but 15
minutes later ``they boarded up the (first) plane with another crew
and they left,'' she said. She said someone asked if that was the
same plane that had maintenance problems and the supervisor
replied, ``It was the only one they had.''
<p>
   ``I don't know if what was wrong with the airplane was fixed,''
she said. ``If they can do two days' work in 15 minutes, they
really are a wonderful airline.''
<p>
   The next day, she told her supervisor and refused to fly again
until she got answers about what happened.
<p>
   ``We took her concerns very seriously,'' ValuJet's Kenyon said.
He said the airline investigated but found no records of
maintenance problems in the log books. ``We took her concerns very
seriously,'' he said. ``We found no discrepancies and nothing wrong
with the aircraft.''
<p>
   He added that Chagares ``was offered various counseling and did
not come back.''
<p>
   Chagares said she was told in early February to start flying or
they would assume she didn't want her job anymore.
<p>
   ``Nobody in that company will say anything, nobody,'' she said.
``That's why that whistleblower law is needed so badly.''
<p>
   While ValuJet's Scott said she was not familiar with the
whistleblower legislation, she said, ``Anything that provides the
airline and its people with a method of guaranteeing a higher level
of safety is great.'' .
</TEXT>
