<PREAMBLE>
BC-DRUNK-BOATERS-COX
HOUSE VOTES TO KEEP DRUNKEN BOAT, PLANE OPERATORS FROM HIDING
BEHIND FEDERAL BANKRUPTCY LAWS
By CHRISTI HARLAN
c.1996 Cox News Service
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   WASHINGTON  &MD;  Seven years ago this month, 22-year-old Deborah Ann
Rock died on Lake Austin when she was hit by the bow and propeller
of a boat that smashed into the idling boat in which she was
sitting.
<p>
   Rock's parents won a $500,000 award from an Austin, Texas, jury
against the pilot of the moving boat, John Greenway. But 3 1/2
years later, the Rocks have yet to collect a penny from Greenway,
thanks to the protection of federal bankruptcy law.
<p>
   That protection should not be available in future cases
involving boats and alcohol, the House decided Tuesday. By a voice
vote, members of the House closed a loophole in bankruptcy law that
shielded drunk pilots of boats and airplanes from liability for
accidents that hurt or kill others.
<p>
   ``In the past, watercraft and aircraft operators have had little
fear of punishment knowing that this loophole existed,'' said U.S.
Rep. Vernon J. Ehlers, R-Mich., the sponsor of the measure. ``With
this bill, the federal government will be doing its part to
supplement what the states . . . are doing to combat drunk boating
and flying.''
<p>
   Bankruptcy law currently allows debtors to cancel most of their
debts, with about a dozen exceptions. Those include federal taxes,
student loans and ``any debt for death or personal injury caused by
the debtor's operation of a motor vehicle'' while intoxicated by
alcohol or drugs.
<p>
   In at least three cases, including the Rocks' case against
Greenway, courts have wrestled with the question of whether boats
are ``motor vehicles'' and whether drunk drivers of boats should be
shielded from liability.
<p>
   ``I'm just stunned that it's a hard question,'' said Karl O.
Bayer Jr. of Austin, the lawyer for two other people who were in
the boat in which Rock was killed. ``I didn't even figure it would
be a close call.''
<p>
   But two courts have agreed with Greenway and his lawyers that
the 21-foot Supra powerboat he was piloting June 30, 1989, was not
a motor vehicle. Those rulings have kept Greenway from having to
pay the judgments won by the passengers and pilot of the other
boat.
<p>
   The legislation approved Tuesday will not affect the Rocks' case
against Greenway, but the case was one of three cited last November
by the House Judiciary Committee when it reported on the need for
the legislation changing the bankruptcy law.
<p>
   The crash occurred on Lake Austin near the Loop 360 bridge as
Rock, two other passengers and the pilot sat on an idle 18-foot
Maxum powerboat. Greenway's boat hit the Maxum from behind and
became airborne, striking and killing Rock and severely injuring
another woman passenger.
<p>
   The wreck happened about an hour before Texas'
boating-while-intoxicated law took effect. Greenway, whose
blood-alcohol level was between 0.09 and 0.11, was indicted on a
misdemeanor charge of criminally negligent homicide and pleaded no
contest to the charge in August 1990. He was sentenced to 30 days
in jail and fined $1,000.
<p>
   Greenway, now a lawyer in Austin, sought bankruptcy-court
protection shortly after a civil-court jury voted in December 1992
to award $500,000 in damages to Rock's parents and a total of
$300,000 to three other people who were on the boat with Rock.
<p>
   A bankruptcy judge in Austin ruled that Greenway could escape
liability for the judgments because a boat is not a motor vehicle
as described in bankruptcy law. That ruling was overturned in April
1995 by U.S. District Judge James Nowlin of Austin, who wrote that
he could ``see no reason why Congress would have been concerned
with drunk driving in one context and not the other.''
<p>
   Earlier this year, Nowlin's ruling was reversed by the 5th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals, which said a boat is not a motor vehicle.
The attorneys for Rock's parents, from the Austin firm of Spivey,
Grigg, Kelly and Knisely, have asked the U.S. Supreme Court to hear
the case.
<p>
   Greenway, reached at his office, declined to comment.
<p>
   ``There's plenty I'd like to say,'' he said, ``but it's still in
court.''
</TEXT>
