RECOVERY VESSELS: VARIED HISTORY AND FUNCTIONS
(For use by New York Times News Service clients)
By DAVID L. CHANDLER
c.1996 The Boston Globe
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   The Navy ships Grasp and Grapple were built to rescue or tow
ships or submarines in distress and to salvage sunken vessels, but
their work this week on the recovery of TWA Flight 800 is not the
first time they have been used to retrieve aircraft  &MD;  or even
spacecraft.
<p>
   Less than two months after it was commissioned, the Grasp, the
older of the two vessels, was used in 1986 to pick up pieces of the
space shuttle Challenger from the sea floor off Florida.
<p>
   The Grapple, commissioned a year later, was once used to recover
two F-14 jets that had crashed in 190 feet of water, although a
Navy spokesman declined to specify where or when this operation
took place. More conventionally, it has towed decommissioned
nuclear submarines to their final ports, it has towed three
minesweepers to the Persian Gulf before the Gulf War, and it helped
with harbor cleanup in the aftermath of Hurricane Hugo.
<p>
   The two ships working on the TWA effort off Long Island are the
most advanced salvage ships in the world, and they are outfitted
with the latest in equipment for surveying the sea floor,
supporting teams of divers and raising debris, the Navy says.
<p>
   For the TWA salvage, the ships' most important equipment are
Remotely Operated Vehicles, or ROVs  &MD;  small unpiloted submersibles,
connected by cables to the ship. The submirsibles carry cameras,
sonar and laser equipment, and claws to grab and retrieve objects.
They are controlled from the ship by operators who watch television
screens displaying the ROVs' sea floor view. They are capable of
diving to 7,200 feet, although the TWA operation is in relatively
shallow water, only 100 to 120 feet deep.
<p>
   Much of the technology they employ is relatively new. In
particular, the advent of the Global Positioning System satellites
should make it much easier for divers to locate precisely specific
targets that have been identified with the side-scan sonar used to
map the area. The system can pinpoint a location to within a few
feet.
<p>
   The robotic submersibles also carry advanced scanning systems
that use a narrow beam of laser light to locate objects on the sea
floor. A small moving mirror reflects the laser beam back and forth
across the bottom, as a light receptor builds up an image of the
debris field. The image is created one line at a time as the
submirsible is towed along, much as a computer's flatbed scanner
translates an image into digital data one line at a time.
<p>
   This is the first time the laser scanner has been used in an
actual salvage operation, said a Navy spokesman, Lt. j.g. Joe
Walker.
<p>
   But even with the best of equipment, the skill of the operator
can make a big difference, said James Bellingham, director of the
underwater vehicle laboratory at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology. For one thing, in the murky environment of the sea
floor, it can be very difficult to get a sense of the scale of
objects located by the sonar or laser devices.
<p>
   To illustrate, Bellingham cited a research project he worked on
in New Hampshire's Lake Winnipesaukee. A submersible found an
object the researchers thought was a coffee cup. Pulled to the
surface, it was found to be a chamber pot. ``We couldn't gauge what
the size was by looking at the video,'' he said.
<p>
   Locating pieces of the aircraft on the ocean floor is difficult
enough; recovering them is even trickier, Bellingham said. ``It's a
tough thing to do, and very much depends on surface conditions,''
he said.
<p>
   There are three basic ways to recover objects: with a ``lifting
bag,'' a canvas bag that is placed around the object and filled
with air to cause it to rise to the surface; using an ROV to grasp
the object in its claws and carry it up; or attaching cables to it
and hoisting it directly to the ship.
<p>
   The ROV is by far the gentlest and the least likely to cause
further damage to the object, said Navy spokesman Walker.
</TEXT>
