MORE THAN 140 FEARED DEAD IN RUSSIAN AIRLINER CRASH IN ARCTIC
(ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)
(bl)
c.1996 N.Y. Times News Service 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   OSLO, Norway  &MD;  A Russian jetliner carrying more than 140 people
 &MD;  mostly coal miners and their families  &MD;  crashed into a mountain
Thursday on the remote Arctic island of Spitsbergen in Norwegian
territory. There appeared to be no survivors, Norwegian authorities
said.
<p>
   The three-engine Tupolev Tu-154 owned by Vnukovo Airlines was
nearing the end of a flight from Moscow when it went off course
amid low clouds and struck Opera Mountain, a 3,000-foot peak six
miles east of Svalbard Airport at Longyearbyen, the island's main
settlement.
<p>
   The passengers were described as Russians and Ukrainians, most
of them workers for the Trust Arktik Ugol mining company. They were
a relief force for an equal number of miners and family members who
had been waiting at the airport to take the same jet back to
Moscow.
<p>
   Russia's ambassador to Norway, Yuri Fokine, said that up to 20
children were aboard the jet, but Norwegian authorities in touch
with the airline maintained that the passenger list comprised 125
adults and 4 children, in addition to either 12 or 14 crew members.
<p>
   Flight controllers reported losing radio contact with the jet at
10:15 a.m. At 12:06 p.m. a Norwegian search party in two
helicopters and a light plane found most of the wreckage on a snowy
plateau, officials said. The rear section of the jet had tumbled
down a cliff, causing a small avalanche.
<p>
   Five rescue workers who landed at the scene determined that
there were no survivors, then left three and a half hours later
because of thickening fog, Norway's Rescue Coordination Center
said. It said the temperature was in the high 30s.
<p>
   Fokine praised the rescue effort in an interview with Norwegian
television and added, ``There was no sign of life when the
helicopters arrived.''
<p>
   A Norwegian minister, Jan Hoifoedt, informed the group waiting
at the airport of the crash.
<p>
   ``The tears flowed,'' Hoifoedt told a radio interviewer. ``Many
had friends, work acquaintances and even some family members
aboard. It is a huge tragedy for so small a community.''
<p>
   Spitsbergen is the largest island in the Svalbard archipelago,
about 350 miles north of the Norwegian mainland. A 1920 treaty gave
Norway ownership of the archipelago, but the Soviet Union acquired
mining rights in 1935.
<p>
   Of Svalbard's population of 2,500, almost two-thirds are
citizens of former Soviet republics. They operate two mines  &MD;  in
Pyramiden and Barentsburg  &MD;  extracting some 600,000 tons of coal a
year, about twice the output of Norwegian mines.
<p>
   Investigators from Oslo and Moscow are not expected to reach the
crash site until Friday morning, when removal of the bodies is to
begin. The Norwegian government was also sending criminal
investigators, though officials said there was no immediate sign of
foul play.
<p>
   Early this evening a Norwegian helicopter crew managed to lift
two prefabricated cabins onto the plateau near the wreckage. From
there, two or three sentries were to make sure the site is not
disturbed during the night.
<p>
   ``There are about 2,000 polar bears on this island,'' said Rune
B. Hansen, the acting governor. ``We haven't seen any around here
lately but they are unpredictable and can suddenly be anywhere.''
<p>
   Though the number of air fatalities in the former Soviet Union
has declined in the last two years, it remains alarmingly high
compared to what it was during the Soviet era.
<p>
   When the Soviet airline Aeroflot was broken up five years ago,
many new air companies were created. Vnukovo Airlines is one of
dozens of these so-called ``babyflots,'' which have been plagued by
lack of cash and poor maintenance. Many if not most of the aircraft
in the Russian fleets are long past retirement age.
<p>
   An official at Vnukova Airlines in Moscow refused to comment
Thursday night on the crash.
</TEXT>
