<PREAMBLE>
BC-VALUJET-NYT
VALUJET GETS PERMISSION TO FLY AGAIN
(bl)
By ADAM BRYANT
c.1996 N.Y. Times News Service 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   The Federal Aviation Administration said Thursday that Valujet
Airlines, grounded for more than two months after a deadly crash in
the Everglades, could start flying again under greater agency
scrutiny.
<p>
   The approval, one of two hurdles the airlines must clear before
resuming service, comes 10 weeks after the agency ordered a halt to
its operations because of systemic safety problems uncovered after
the crash on May 11 of a Valujet DC-9 that killed all 110 people
aboard.
<p>
   Valujet also received tentative approval Thursday to resume
flights from the Department of Transportation, which evaluates the
competence and safety record of an airline's managers as well as
the carrier's economic health.
<p>
   With the department's decision, a seven-day comment period
begins during which the agency will receive any objections to
letting Valujet resume service.
<p>
   It will review the objections, give Valujet a chance to respond
and then make its final determination. If Valujet clears this
second hurdle with no objections, it could be back in the air as
soon as next Thursday.
<p>
   Transportation officials, however, are likely to hear again
about Valujet from the Association of Flight Attendants, a union
representing flight attendants at the airline.
<p>
   The union has repeatedly complained to the transportation
department in recent weeks that Valujet's senior officers are not
fit to run a safe airline in large measure because of the lapses
found at Valujet.
<p>
   The department said Thursday that it had taken into account the
union's recent objections in making its tentative decision. A
lawyer representing the union, Robert S. Clayman, said Thursday
that the union planned to file more complaints.
<p>
   ``What the DOT has suggested today is that the men in charge of
the airline were in no way responsible for all of the safety
violations that caused their shutdown,'' Mr. Clayman said in an
interview. ``We thought it was one strike and you're out, not trial
and error.''
<p>
   John V. Coleman, director of aviation analysis at the
department, said in a conference call with reporters that the two
top officers of Valujet  &MD;  Robert Priddy, chairman, and Lewis H.
Jordan, president  &MD;  had good safety records over their long airline
careers. ``Nothing in their background suggests that they have been
noncompliant with federal regulations of any kind,'' he said.
<p>
   The aviation agency said Thursday that Valujet had been approved
to resume service with nine aircraft, and could quickly add up to
six more. Valujet had 51 aircraft in its fleet when the airline was
shut down June 17. The safety lapses that led to Valujet's
grounding were not directly linked to the cause of the crash.
<p>
   Since the grounding of Valujet, the airline had met the agency's
requirements for resuming service, including revising its
maintenance program and procedures, revising its organizational
structure and adding new maintenance and management personnel, and
retraining pilots and maintenance workers, the FAA said Thursday.
The airline also will initially fly only one type of DC-9.
<p>
   The FAA also said it would raise the number of inspectors
assigned to Valujet to seven from three, and closely scrutinize its
plans to expand once it resumes flying.
<p>
   Valujet executives said Thursday that they hoped to resume
service to Atlanta and four as yet unnamed cities in about two
weeks.
<p>
   The FAA appears to have changed its approach to speaking
publicly about the safety of Valujet. Immediately after the May 11
crash, top FAA and DOT officials declared Valujet a safe airline.
<p>
   When asked Thursday whether the FAA now considered Valujet safe,
Bill White, deputy director of flight standards at the FAA,
responded only by saying that Valujet was in compliance with safety
regulations.
<p>
   ``It's up to Valujet to maintain the safe operation of the
aircraft,'' he said.
</TEXT>
